docker pull mongo
The command docker pull mongo downloads the official MongoDB Docker image from Docker Hub to your local machine. Because you didn't specify a version tag (like mongo:6.0), Docker will automatically download the latest version.

Here is what you typically need to do next to actually run the database.

Starting your MongoDB Container
Once the image finishes downloading, you can spin up a MongoDB container using the docker run command. Here is a standard, secure way to start it:

Bash
docker run -d --name my-mongodb -p 27017:27017 -e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_USERNAME=admin -e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_PASSWORD=secretpassword mongo
What these flags do:
-d: Runs the container in "detached" mode, meaning it runs quietly in the background, freeing up your terminal.

--name my-mongodb: Assigns a custom, recognizable name to your container.

-p 27017:27017: Maps the default MongoDB port (27017) from inside the container to port 27017 on your local machine so your apps can connect to it.

-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_USERNAME=admin: An environment variable that sets up your root database user.

-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_PASSWORD=secretpassword: An environment variable that sets the password for your root user.

mongo: Tells Docker which image to use to build this container.
